context: The Bivalent (2vHPV) vaccine, with the brand name Cervarix, is one of the three human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccines licensed for use in the United States. It targets HPV types 16 and 18. The vaccine is manufactured by GlaxoSmithKline using the Trichoplusia ni insect cell line infected with L1 encoding recombinant baculovirus. It contains an adjuvant of 500 µg aluminum hydroxide and 50 µg 3-O-desacyl-4' monophosphoryl lipid A. Volume per dose is 0.5 ml, and administration is done intramuscularly.

context: The Quadrivalent (4vHPV) vaccine, with the brand name Gardasil, is one of the three human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccines licensed for use in the United States. It targets HPV types 6, 11, 16, and 18. The vaccine is manufactured by Merck and Co., Inc. using Saccharomyces cerevisiae (Baker's yeast) that expresses L1. It contains an adjuvant of 225 µg amorphous aluminum hydroxyphosphate sulfate. Volume per dose is 0.5 ml, and administration is done intramuscularly.
